solute truths, defy established boundaries of literary genres and challenge concepts of national, gender and individual identity. The authors studied in this book---Reinaldo Arenas, Leonardo Padura Fuentes, Abilio Estévez, Daína Chaviano, Yanitzia Canetti, and Zoé Valdés---are placed beyond the dichotomy of outside and inside Cuba in order to focus on the fluidity and heterogeneity of Cuban culture displayed in its literature. This study establishes similarities and differences in the way these authors create polyphonic texts that question whether notions of country and nation coincide in novels that respond to economic hardship, political and social changes, issues of cubanía, and exile. Ángela Dorado-Otero is Postdoctoral Research Fellow in Iberian and Latin American Studies at Queen Mary University of London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCuban fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aModern History. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aCuban Authors.  aCuban Culture.  aCuban Fiction.  aCuban Identity.  aCuban Literature.  aCuban Novel.  aPost-Civil War Period.  aÁngela Dorado-Otero.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204234140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782042341423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782042341/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles